# LC-NE System and Context-Dependent Brain Network Switching

**Evidence Base for Noradrenergic Control of Role Switching**

<a id="header"></a><a id="content"></a><a id="Xccdfc35240cf66bd8e072ab0c30d08b1c8cfcd5"></a># LC‐NE System and Context‑Dependent Brain Network Switching

<a id="X57663a465b14aebfc5309db4e436e168cb41d32"></a>## A\. Mechanistic Evidence \(Causal LC‐NE Manipulations\)

![](data:image/png;base64,)  
*Optogenetic stimulation of LC in mice \(lower panel\) increased baseline LC firing and accelerated rule\-switching performance after a context change \(blue = fast adaptation vs red = slow\)*[*\[1\]*](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9662304/#:~:text=optogenetically%20tagged%20neurons%20in%20the,LC%20activity%20and%20behavioral%20flexibility)*\. This illustrates a causal link between LC activity and behavioral flexibility\.*

- __Optogenetic LC activation in rodents \(fMRI & electrophysiology\):__ Pattern\-specific stimulation of the locus coeruleus produces distinct brain\-wide network effects\. Using mice, Grimm *et al\.* \(2024\) showed that moderate __tonic__ LC firing engaged higher\-order __associative__ regions, whereas phasic __burst__ firing biased the brain toward __sensory__ processing networks[\[2\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-024-01755-8?error=cookies_not_supported&code=97e11b13-dcbf-41f9-8ed7-67431002bfad#:~:text=Noradrenaline%20,These%20activation)[\[3\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-024-01755-8?error=cookies_not_supported&code=97e11b13-dcbf-41f9-8ed7-67431002bfad#:~:text=that%20tonic%20and%20burst,regulation%20of%20global%20circuit%20operations)\. These firing modes also reconfigured the brain’s __topological__ network architecture in line with cortical hierarchy \(tonic LC coupling frontoparietal areas, burst recruiting sensory cortices\)[\[4\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-024-01755-8?error=cookies_not_supported&code=97e11b13-dcbf-41f9-8ed7-67431002bfad#:~:text=electrophysiology%20and%20functional%20magnetic%20resonance,regulation%20of%20global%20circuit%20operations)\. *Strengths:* Precise causal control of LC output with optogenetics and multimodal readouts \(photometry, fMRI\) confirms that different LC‐NE dynamics actively __switch network configurations__\. *Limitations:* Experiments in anesthetized/head\-fixed mice; translating specific LC firing patterns to human “self\-state” changes remains inferential\.
- __Chemogenetic LC stimulation in mice \(resting\-state fMRI\):__ Strong global activation of LC neurons via DREADDs caused __rapid reconfiguration__ of functional connectivity across the whole brain\. Zerbi *et al\.* \(2019\) observed a __brain\-wide__ increase in network connectivity, most pronounced in the __salience__ and amygdalar networks, following LC‐NE activation[\[5\]](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3334983#:~:text=possible%20in%20humans%2C%20studies%20have,1%20adrenoceptors%20across%20the)\. Connectivity changes correlated with regional adrenoceptor gene expression, linking molecular NE targets to network effects[\[6\]](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3334983#:~:text=rapidly%20interrupts%20ongoing%20behavior%20and,These%20results%20represent%20the%20first)\. This provides a __causal map__ of LC\-driven network shifts, demonstrating that LC activation can “favor salience processing” under high arousal[\[7\]](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3334983#:~:text=The%20locus%20coeruleus%20,wide)\. *Strengths:* First direct __whole\-brain connectivity__ mapping after selective LC activation; confirms a causal NE influence on large\-scale network organization[\[8\]](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3334983#:~:text=and%20transcript%20levels%20of%20alpha,increased%20vigilance%20and%20threat%20detection)\. *Limits:* Used exogenous activation \(potentially non\-physiological tonic drive\) and anesthesia during fMRI; broad activation may not capture finer context\-specific LC firing nuances\.
- __NE reuptake inhibition in primates \(pharmacological fMRI\):__ Elevating endogenous NE levels likewise induces network reorganization\. __Atomoxetine__ \(an NE reuptake blocker\) administered to monkeys at rest triggered __large\-scale connectivity__ changes[\[9\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=The%20locus%20coeruleus%E2%80%93norepinephrine%20,and%20interactions%20between%20associative%20and)\. Notably, the frontoparietal __executive__ network uncoupled from other circuits and switched from negative to __positive correlation__ with a brainstem network encompassing the LC[\[10\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=networks,central%20feature%20within%20this%20reorganization)\. This pharmacological boost of NE provided the __first empirical evidence__ that increasing LC\-NE tone drives __whole\-brain network reconfiguration__ in vivo[\[11\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=sensory%E2%80%93motor%20networks%20as%20well%20as,central%20feature%20within%20this%20reorganization)\. *Strength:* Demonstrates in a primate model that NE surges can “reset” inter\-network relationships \(especially involving frontoparietal vs\. sensorimotor networks\)[\[10\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=networks,central%20feature%20within%20this%20reorganization)\. *Weakness:* Resting\-state design – no specific behavioral context tested; systemic drug effects \(e\.g\. on dopamine\) could confound, though the __network reset__ aligns with theoretical predictions[\[12\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=properties%20revealed%20in%20animal%20models,projections%20of%20the%20LC%E2%80%93NE%20system)\.
- __LC spiking and task switching in rodents:__ McBurney\-Lin *et al\.* \(2022\) recorded LC neuron activity during a rule\-switching task and directly manipulated LC firing\. They found that higher __baseline__ LC firing after a rule change predicted faster switching to the new context, whereas lower LC activity led to sluggish adaptation[\[1\]](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9662304/#:~:text=optogenetically%20tagged%20neurons%20in%20the,LC%20activity%20and%20behavioral%20flexibility)\. Crucially, __optogenetically increasing__ LC tonic activity immediately __accelerated__ behavioral switching and improved performance[\[1\]](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9662304/#:~:text=optogenetically%20tagged%20neurons%20in%20the,LC%20activity%20and%20behavioral%20flexibility)\. This establishes a causal chain from LC\-NE output to __behavioral mode__ transitions \(here, shifting decision\-making strategy\)\. *Strengths:* Millisecond\-resolution recordings and perturbations pinpoint LC’s role in __adaptive cognitive flexibility__\. *Limits:* Conducted in mice on a specific sensory rule task – it shows LC can mediate context\-dependent __behavioral__ switching, but the underlying brain network changes were not directly measured \(implied through faster engagement of the new rule\)\.

<a id="Xe116fe682dbb5db40850f99e9fb259272a860be"></a>## B\. Correlational Evidence \(LC‐NE Activity & Network Dynamics\)

- __LC\-NE phasic bursts and network reconfiguration \(human fMRI\):__ In humans, spontaneous fluctuations in LC activity correlate with rapid network shifts\. Using high\-resolution 7T fMRI, Munn *et al\.* \(2021\) identified brief __phasic LC “bursts”__ \(inferred from brainstem BOLD signals\) that preceded increased global __integration__ among cortical networks[\[13\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=match%20at%20L270%20correlation%20between,1d%29%20within%20the%20cerebral)\. Specifically, a surge in LC activity was followed by heightened synchronization of frontoparietal executive regions \(greater inter\-regional coordination\), while conversely segregating some visual, limbic, and motor areas[\[14\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=match%20at%20L275%20Fig,the%20synchronization%20of%20the%20frontoparietal)\. These arousal\-driven connectivity changes were time\-locked to internal shifts in conscious mental state in meditators[\[15\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=dimensional%20energy%20landscape%20of%20cortical,of%20the%20cerebral%20cortex%20and)\. In other words, when the LC fired in bursts, the brain’s functional networks reorganized and people reported shifts in __awareness or mental context__\. *Strengths:* Captures __time\-resolved network topology__ changes linked to endogenous LC activity in humans, supporting that LC\-NE drives large\-scale network flexibility in real time[\[16\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=reconfiguration%20of%20low,all%20p)\. *Weaknesses:* Correlational – LC BOLD and network changes are concurrent, so causality is inferred \(though temporal ordering suggests LC leading\); fMRI signals are slow and can reflect vascular effects \(the authors note NE influences cerebral blood flow[\[17\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=The%20vascular%20nature%20of%20the,haemodynamic%20and%20neural%20responses%20that), though coupled neural effects are strongly indicated\)[\[18\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=and%20massed%20neural%20action%20in,mediate%20alterations%20in%20conscious%20awareness)\.
- __Arousal, event boundaries, and memory \(pupillometry & fMRI\):__ Phasic LC\-NE activity also correlates with how the brain __partitions experiences__ into distinct memory episodes\. Clewett *et al\.* \(2025\) showed that when participants encountered a meaningful __context shift__ or event boundary in a story, it evoked a spike in arousal – indexed by pupil dilation – along with heightened LC activation on fMRI[\[19\]](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40482639/#:~:text=Memories%20reflect%20the%20ebb%20and,transient%20LC%20effects%2C%20indirect%20structural)\. These LC\-linked arousal bursts __predicted__ the degree of separation between adjacent events in memory \(greater LC/pupil response \-> the hippocampus formed more distinct representations for pre\- vs\. post\-boundary events\)[\[19\]](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40482639/#:~:text=Memories%20reflect%20the%20ebb%20and,transient%20LC%20effects%2C%20indirect%20structural)[\[20\]](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40482639/#:~:text=Boundaries%2C%20furthermore%2C%20promote%20temporal%20pattern,episodes%20that%20define%20episodic%20memory)\. The authors interpret this as an LC\-mediated __“memory reset”__ mechanism, wherein a surge of NE at context change __reconfigures hippocampal networks__ to encode a new episode[\[21\]](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40482639/#:~:text=reduced%20arousal,episodes%20that%20define%20episodic%20memory)\. Interestingly, individuals with chronically high LC tone \(as measured by neuromelanin MRI and baseline pupil\) showed blunted phasic responses at boundaries, suggesting __over\-arousal__ can disrupt optimal network reset[\[22\]](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40482639/#:~:text=those%20same%20transition%20points,episodes%20that%20define%20episodic%20memory)\. *Strengths:* Multimodal evidence \(pupil, LC\-MRI, fMRI\) in humans linking __LC activity to cognitive context switching__, here in the domain of episodic memory encoding\. *Limitations:* Still correlational – LC activity was inferred, not controlled; focuses on hippocampal and memory\-related networks \(self\-referential “internal context” processing\) rather than mapping the entire connectome\.
- __Acute stress and network switching \(human pharmacology\):__ Context\-dependent self\-state changes \(e\.g\. going from calm to __stressed/vigilant__\) also implicate LC\-NE modulation of networks\. Hermans *et al\.* \(2011\) found that inducing acute psychosocial __stress__ in healthy adults caused a marked shift in large\-scale network coupling: the __salience network__ \(including amygdala and insula\) became hyper\-connected, while the default\-mode and executive control networks were down\-regulated\. Crucially, they demonstrated this effect was __noradrenergically driven__ – blocking NE signaling with __propranolol__ \(β\-adrenergic antagonist\) prevented the salience\-network dominance seen under stress[\[23\]](https://pdodds.w3.uvm.edu/files/papers/others/2011/hermans2011a.pdf#:~:text=Our%20findings%20establish%20a%20causal,Although%20functional%20connectivity%20within%20the)\. In contrast, blocking cortisol synthesis had different effects, isolating NE as a key driver of the network reconfiguration[\[24\]](https://pdodds.w3.uvm.edu/files/papers/others/2011/hermans2011a.pdf#:~:text=To%20investigate%20whether%20functional%20connectiv%02ity,dual%20architecture%20of%20cortical%20attentional)[\[25\]](https://pdodds.w3.uvm.edu/files/papers/others/2011/hermans2011a.pdf#:~:text=A%20pivotal%20question%20following%20from,were%20extended%20with%20a%20threat)\. Their conclusion: __stress\-induced LC\-NE activity causally “flips” the brain’s connectivity__ into a vigilance mode, supporting rapid detection of threats[\[23\]](https://pdodds.w3.uvm.edu/files/papers/others/2011/hermans2011a.pdf#:~:text=Our%20findings%20establish%20a%20causal,Although%20functional%20connectivity%20within%20the)\. *Strengths:* Combines fMRI with pharmacological manipulation to establish a __causal link__ between elevated NE \(as occurs via LC under stress\) and large\-scale network reorganization \(increased connectivity of a salience/alertness network\)[\[23\]](https://pdodds.w3.uvm.edu/files/papers/others/2011/hermans2011a.pdf#:~:text=Our%20findings%20establish%20a%20causal,Although%20functional%20connectivity%20within%20the)\. *Weaknesses:* Stress is a complex state – while propranolol implicates NE, downstream effects \(heart rate, etc\.\) could also influence fMRI signals\. Nonetheless, this is strong in\-vivo human evidence that changing __contextual mode__ \(relaxed vs\. alarmed\) involves LC\-NE mediated network switching\.

<a id="X8093236ff02ab9845b8a30eb35a493246d85074"></a>## C\. Theoretical and Computational Perspectives

- __Adaptive Gain and Mode Switching Theory:__ The LC\-NE system has long been theorized to regulate __global cognitive mode__ via its firing patterns[\[26\]](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9662304/#:~:text=and%20Shapiro%2C%202009%20%3B%20Tervo,40%2C%202004%20%3B%20%2042)\. Aston\-Jones & Cohen’s __adaptive gain theory__ \(2005\) proposed that moderate, phasic LC firing increases “gain” in task\-relevant neural circuits \(sharpening focus and facilitating exploitative, goal\-directed behavior\), whereas high, tonic LC firing leads to broad disengagement from the current focus and promotes an exploratory, __context\-switching state__[\[26\]](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9662304/#:~:text=and%20Shapiro%2C%202009%20%3B%20Tervo,40%2C%202004%20%3B%20%2042)[\[12\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=properties%20revealed%20in%20animal%20models,projections%20of%20the%20LC%E2%80%93NE%20system)\. This framework aligns with later evidence that LC firing shifts correspond to __role shifts__ – e\.g\. toggling between focused execution of a task vs\. scanning for alternative opportunities \(exploration\)[\[12\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=properties%20revealed%20in%20animal%20models,projections%20of%20the%20LC%E2%80%93NE%20system)\. It provides a conceptual link between neuromodulator dynamics and the __self’s operational state__, suggesting LC\-NE is a switch that toggles the brain between modes of engagement\.
- __“Network Reset” Hypothesis:__ LC\-NE activation has been likened to hitting a global “reset” button on the brain’s networks[\[12\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=properties%20revealed%20in%20animal%20models,projections%20of%20the%20LC%E2%80%93NE%20system)\. Bouret & Sara \(2005\) first posited that a phasic burst of LC activity in response to a salient event __interrupts ongoing neural activity patterns__ and __reconfigures networks__ to optimally respond to the new context[\[12\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=properties%20revealed%20in%20animal%20models,projections%20of%20the%20LC%E2%80%93NE%20system)\. Computational models support this: a transient increase in neural gain \(simulating an LC\-NE surge\) can destabilize the current attractor state of cortical activity, allowing the system to __jump to a new state__ configured for the incoming situation[\[27\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=The%20results%20of%20our%20state,forcing%20a%20broader%20landscape%20flattening)[\[28\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=notion%20of%20a%20network%20reset39,adaptive%20benefits%20across%20a%20spectrum)\. This mechanism explains how the brain can rapidly adapt when one’s __role or context changes__ – e\.g\. switching from a “resting self” network configuration to a “task\-oriented” configuration – without requiring slow structural changes\.
- __Dynamic Energy Landscape Models:__ Recent theoretical work \(Shine, 2019; 2021\) casts brain activity as navigating a low\-dimensional energy landscape of network states\. In this view, neuromodulators like NE alter the __shape of the landscape__, making transitions easier or harder\. Empirical findings by Shine and colleagues showed that LC\-NE bursts __“flatten” the energy landscape__, effectively lowering barriers between different brain states[\[29\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=The%20results%20of%20our%20state,of%20large%2C%20unexpected%20changes%2055%2C39)\. This leads to more __integrative, globally connected__ brain configurations \(facilitating communication across networks\) or, if LC activation is intense, a wholesale reset of network topology during big contextual changes[\[30\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=mediated%20energy%20landscape%20flattening%20is,bursts%20accentuate%20energy%20wells%20is)[\[31\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=Importantly%2C%20this%20capacity%20could%20confer,of%20large%2C%20unexpected%20changes%2055%2C39)\. Such __arousal\-mediated reconfiguration__ has been directly linked to changes in conscious state[\[32\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=linked56%20%2C%2090,mediate%20alterations%20in%20conscious%20awareness)\. In other words, LC\-NE provides a knob for the brain to smoothly transition into a new network state \(or self\-state\) by adjusting the stability of current state dynamics[\[32\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=linked56%20%2C%2090,mediate%20alterations%20in%20conscious%20awareness)[\[33\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=In%20conclusion%2C%20we%20leveraged%20a,supports%20changes%20in%20conscious%20awareness)\. This theoretical framing dovetails with the idea that our brain can fluidly switch __roles or mindsets__ by neurochemically pushing itself into a different basin of attraction in the network state space\.
- __Role\-Based Self\-System Transitions \(RPS theory\):__ The evidence above suggests that LC\-NE could serve as a biological __trigger for role shifts__ as described in RPS theory\. When an individual changes self\-state or social role \(e\.g\. shifting from a caregiving role to an analytical professional role\), the brain must reconfigure which networks dominate – perhaps dialing down the default\-mode \(self\-referential\) network and ramping up a task\-positive executive network, or vice versa\. The LC’s broad projections and modulatory effects are well\-suited to orchestrate such global shifts[\[34\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-024-01755-8?error=cookies_not_supported&code=97e11b13-dcbf-41f9-8ed7-67431002bfad#:~:text=The%20brain%E2%80%99s%20capacity%20to%20rapidly,behavior%20and%20rapid%20adaptation%3F%20Over)[\[35\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-024-01755-8?error=cookies_not_supported&code=97e11b13-dcbf-41f9-8ed7-67431002bfad#:~:text=shifts%2C%20while%20stably%20balancing%20ongoing,sleep%20and%20wake%20cycles%2C%20cognition)\. For instance, an unexpected change in context that demands a new role will activate LC phasically, releasing NE that __augments inter\-regional coordination__ and __promotes a new coalition__ of brain areas suited to the role’s demands[\[30\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=mediated%20energy%20landscape%20flattening%20is,bursts%20accentuate%20energy%20wells%20is)[\[36\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=Importantly%2C%20this%20capacity%20could%20confer,By%20accentuating%20energy%20wells)\. At the same time, this surge effectively __resets prior network configurations__ \(e\.g\. suspending the previous self\-state’s dominant network\)[\[37\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=Importantly%2C%20this%20capacity%20could%20confer,bursts%20accentuate%20energy%20wells%20is)\. The result is a rapid transition in the functional connectivity pattern – as seen with internal shifts in conscious awareness accompanied by LC\-mediated network changes[\[15\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=dimensional%20energy%20landscape%20of%20cortical,of%20the%20cerebral%20cortex%20and)[\[16\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=reconfiguration%20of%20low,all%20p)\. *In summary, the LC‐NE system’s ability to flexibly toggle brain networks on and off in a context\-dependent manner provides a plausible neurobiological mechanism for the “role switches” posited by RPS theory\.* Every time we shift into a different mode of self \(with distinct goals, mindsets, or social identities\), a phasic burst or tonic change in LC activity may be helping to __reconfigure our brain’s network ensemble__ to match that new self\-state\.

__Sources:__ The above evidence is drawn from peer\-reviewed studies spanning optogenetic and chemogenetic experiments in animals[\[2\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-024-01755-8?error=cookies_not_supported&code=97e11b13-dcbf-41f9-8ed7-67431002bfad#:~:text=Noradrenaline%20,These%20activation)[\[5\]](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3334983#:~:text=possible%20in%20humans%2C%20studies%20have,1%20adrenoceptors%20across%20the), pharmacological and fMRI studies in monkeys and humans[\[9\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=The%20locus%20coeruleus%E2%80%93norepinephrine%20,and%20interactions%20between%20associative%20and)[\[23\]](https://pdodds.w3.uvm.edu/files/papers/others/2011/hermans2011a.pdf#:~:text=Our%20findings%20establish%20a%20causal,Although%20functional%20connectivity%20within%20the), cognitive neuroscience experiments with pupillometry and imaging[\[19\]](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40482639/#:~:text=Memories%20reflect%20the%20ebb%20and,transient%20LC%20effects%2C%20indirect%20structural), and recent theoretical reviews[\[12\]](https://academic.oup.com/cercor/article/27/10/4691/3056438#:~:text=properties%20revealed%20in%20animal%20models,projections%20of%20the%20LC%E2%80%93NE%20system)[\[27\]](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-26268-x?error=cookies_not_supported&code=32eaa6c1-03ed-41fb-813b-cf555334b0ed#:~:text=The%20results%20of%20our%20state,forcing%20a%20broader%20landscape%20flattening)\. These convergent findings support the view that LC\-NE activity mediates adaptive network switching associated with changes in context, state, or role\.
